MARYLAND

What is the overall number of juveniles currently serving a life sentence?

There are 312 juveniles serving a life sentence. 99% of juvenile prisoners are male. ***

What is the racial breakdown of juvenile lifers in each state?

When we look at the racial breakdown above, we see that when we compare to the overall prison population, there are disporportionately more black people (69% of all MD prisoners are black compared to 77% of juveniles) compared to white people, where the situation is the opposite (25% of all MD prisoners are white compared to 14% of juveniles). With hispanic people the difference is small, only 1%.

Has there been a change since 2016, the date of a key supreme court case, in the number of juvenile lifers in each state? If so, what is the change.

Maryland has only released 3 people so far, hence this question doesnt apply here. Yet its still interesting to see how the numbers have changed in the past.

We use both admission dates and offence dates, because MDs Department of Correction doesnt have offense dates for all the juveniles, so they use admission dates for some of them. The graphs show the incarceration rate of juvenile liferspeaked in the mid-ninenties and started to fall ever since.

There isnt a sharp fall in sentencing juveniles to serve life sentences after 2014 amd 2016, but were still waiting to hear back from MD about whether they gave us data about all juvenile lifers or lifers with the chance of parole.

How many of them have been resentenced and released

Aronund 82 % of juveniles have been either resentenced to no longer life or released. 15% are waiting to be either resentenced or released. Three people have died and nine (1.7%) have been resentenced but sentenced to serve life in prison.

MICHIGAN

What is the overall number of juveniles in each state currently serving a life sentence?

There are 368 juveniles serving a life sentence. 97% of juvenile prisoners are male.

What is the racial breakdown of juvenile lifers in each state?

Michigan differs from Maryland and Pennsylvania, because the racial breakdown is almost entirely in line with the racial breakdwon in total prison population. What is more, unlike MD and PA, it doesnt have notably less white juveniles compared to overall white population.

Has there been a change since 2016, the date of a key supreme court case, in the number of juvenile lifers in each state?

Similarly to MD and PA, incarceration rate of juvenile lifers peaked in mid-nineties and then started to fall. Its notable that there isnt a juvenile who has been sentenced after 2015. In parallel, theres a steep rise in resentencing after the 2014 and 2016 supreme court decisions.

The graphs show, how the increase in incarceration rates affected black juveniles so much more than white or hispanic youth. This applies for all three states in our analysis.

Overall, half of Michigan juvenile lifers have gotten a resentence. - 7% of all juveniles have been released - 38% have gotten a new sentence instead of life sentence(most of them got either 20-60 or 30-60 years, some 40-60) - 12 % people are either waiting for a set resentence hearing to begin or their decision - 4% got their resentence, but they were again given a life sentence - rest of them, 39%, are serving life and theres yet no information about their future resentencing

Its notewrothy, that almost half of people who got resentenced back to life (7 juveniles) are from Kent County. When it comes to nr of juveniles per person, then Kent is 18th, yet with absolute numbers (24 peopl) its 4th. So, Kent County doesnt particularly stand out, so something else might be going on. The offense dates for re-lifers are all different, so its not one horrific crime. More reporting is needed.

Lets look into counties more deeply. Graphs below show the status of resentenced juveniles in Michigan counties. The bars show the porportion of resentence decision in comparison to the entire juvenile lifer population in this country. Simply put we see that St Clair and Ottawa have high life-to-life columns, because they only have so little juveniles to begin with. Whereas Macomb and Kent actually stand out by resentencing people back to life more than one would excpect.

When we throw race into the mix, we see that as a whole, more hispanic and white people are resentenced to life more than black people?

Is it because black people live in more liberal counties or were their trials in 1990s less fair? We migth wanna pull in red or blue counties for the first comparison.

When we look at the ages of released people, we see that there are more old people among black released people.
